            <arrangement id="aspace_da9a7be01fb3d814b0a2904cc7840017">
               <head>Arrangement</head>
               <p>Arranged alphabetically.</p>
            </arrangement>
            <scopecontent id="aspace_f58365fd06722e90e7bd6f46479aad11">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>The series consists of correspondence, some printed material, and occasional manuscripts, collected by Jaffe from authors and artists who collaborated with Williams. Most letters were written by Williams and document joint projects with collaborators. The most substantive material relates to Thomas A. Clark.</p>
            </scopecontent>
            <c id="ref14" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Atchley, Dana Winslow</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1968-1988</unitdate>
                  <container containerid="39002091633306"
                             id="aspace_d7e744efe6eb7a6e00675c3f7a386986"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">1</container>
                  <container id="aspace_c909f7b3263e06e877ba6abe857dfd48"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_d7e744efe6eb7a6e00675c3f7a386986">1</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_c12784b55cfd9ec1d09aaca31c735978">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Correspondence, mostly from 1968 to 1971, that documents the publication, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Six Rusticated, Wall-Eyed Poems</part>
                     </title> (1969) and graphic design work Atchley completed for Jonathan Williams and Nicholas Dean for <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Blues &amp; Roots, Rue &amp; Bluets: A Garland for the Appalachians</part>
                     </title> (1971). Other correspondents include Dean and Michael A. Loeb, who served as representative for Grossman. It also includes a letter from Atchley to Jaffe about the correspondence.</p>
                  <p>Material created by Atchley in the graphic design of <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Blues &amp; Roots, Rue &amp; Bluets: A Garland for the Appalachians</part>
                     </title> is available in Series II, Manuscripts and Galley Proofs.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="ref16" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Clark, Thomas A.</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1970-1990</unitdate>
                  <container containerid="39002091633306"
                             id="aspace_26769504d2f548a25a69e477ed78eb89"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">1</container>
                  <container id="aspace_76299fc13fda689681f7917ea933c578"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_26769504d2f548a25a69e477ed78eb89">2-14</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_4b15ef7de9416b64cc2fb460f2715410">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Correspondence, mostly from 1970 to 1980, documents Clark's projects for The Jargon Society, including <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Some Particulars</part>
                     </title> (1971); <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>A Still Life</part>
                     </title>, with Ian Gardner (1977), and <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Ways Through Bracken</part>
                     </title> (1980). Other topics include disagreements between Williams and Ian Hamilton Finlay, as well as his own financial and personal tribulations.</p>
                  <p>Manuscripts and publications intermingled throughout the correspondence include a typed manuscript by Williams for a poem, "A Wee Tot for Catullus;" a memorial essay written by Williams for his father, Thomas Benjamin Williams (1898-1974); copies of The Jargon Society cards and postcards; and a proof copy of <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Ways Through Bracken</part>
                     </title>.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="ref18" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Gardner, Ian</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1972-1990</unitdate>
                  <container containerid="39002091633306"
                             id="aspace_82efe16055082a7e8eeb7ea73af90fab"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">1</container>
                  <container id="aspace_6a4d224f543da4c9d0c1f6a0adff673a"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_82efe16055082a7e8eeb7ea73af90fab">15</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_f80ef7718bc59b2e72d3bf2df1c2442e">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Correspondence that documents <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Pairidaeza: A Celebration in Lithography &amp; Poetry for the Garden at Levens Hall, Westmoreland</part>
                     </title> (1975). Other topics include shared acquaintances and domestic affairs, as well as the difficult temperament of Ian Hamilton Finlay. The correspondence also includes a single letter to Gardner from Thomas Meyer.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="ref20" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Phillips, Tom</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1966-1989</unitdate>
                  <container containerid="39002091633298"
                             id="aspace_6fed3af19112152b9d4e6aad354e2c45"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">2</container>
                  <container id="aspace_548d9197ebf69f9457f8e1895a263c6f"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_6fed3af19112152b9d4e6aad354e2c45">16</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_c7636838445858ecfa70df260b4b6368">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Correspondence by Williams, mostly from 1969 to 1980, that chiefly documents, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Imaginary Postcards</part>
                     </title> (1975). Other correspondence includes letters from Thomas Meyer, a single letter from Phillips to Williams, as well as a letter from Phillips to Jaffe about the correspondence and publications.</p>
                  <p>Several publications by The Jargon Society are intermingled throughout the correspondence.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="ref22" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Roman, U. Grant</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1962-1965</unitdate>
                  <container containerid="39002091633298"
                             id="aspace_6683ffff2d61dd2cf1637f86343cf924"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">2</container>
                  <container id="aspace_e6ba10d90f97e86ec5130ca099e1319d"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_6683ffff2d61dd2cf1637f86343cf924">17</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_a5b137e8cb2e0b68a209866f2c61d402">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Correspondence and related material originally compiled by Roman that primarily documents the publishing of Jonathan Williams, <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
                        <part>Lines About Hills Above Lakes</part>
                     </title> (1964). It documents the planning for the book and Williams' dissatisfaction with the final publication. Includes copies of correspondence between Williams and Henry Wenning, a bookseller in New Haven, Connecticut, who introduced Williams to Roman.</p>
                  <p>Related material includes prospectuses for the book, pamphlets about Williams, a printed resume for Williams, and a promotional pamphlet for the Nantahala Foundation.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="ref24" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Smith, Henry Holmes</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1967-1980</unitdate>
                  <container containerid="39002091633298"
                             id="aspace_0e33ff917fc9a19ad1fa9ae7c1369d08"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">2</container>
                  <container id="aspace_4c8976f301a0d3ec702efc7f1e1898de"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_0e33ff917fc9a19ad1fa9ae7c1369d08">18</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_11ff05933f9532b675b196aa503e3f63">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Correspondence by Williams that discusses his projects and their shared acquaintances, including Clarence John Laughlin.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="ref26" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Webb, Jon Edgar</unittitle>
